179","Abt 1210":"circa 1210","Bef 1242":"vóór 1242","1210":"1210","1 August 1242":"1 augustus 1242","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1184–1 August 1242":"about 1184–1 August 1242","1179–Male":"1179–Deceased","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1180–1242":"1180–1242","1210–1256":"1210–1256","1141–Male":"1141–Deceased","about 1193":"about 1193","1242":"1242","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","1180":"1180","Abt 1184":"about 1184","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1179":"1179","Abt 1210":"about 1210","Bef 1242":"before 1242","1210":"1210","1 August 1242":"1 August 1242","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chevaler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Pierre, Patrice, Serge, Gabrielle, Jacques, Marcel, Michel, Raoul, Sylvain, Adelore, Antoine.","French: from Old French <i>chevalier</i> ‘knight’ (literally ‘horseman, rider’, from Late Latin <i>caballarius</i>, a derivative of <i>caballus</i> ‘horse’). In the Middle Ages only men of comparative wealth were able to afford the upkeep of a riding horse. It is likely that in the majority of cases the surname was originally a nickname, or an occupational name for a knight's servant, rather than a status name, for most men of the knightly class belonged to noble families which had more specific surnames derived from their estates. This was a name of Norman origin in England but probably did not survive the medieval period, and was later reintroduced by Huguenot refugees.","History: Joseph Chevalier from Dieppe in Seine-Maritime, France, married Françoise-Marthe Barton in Montreal, QC, in 1670. Pierre Chevalier <i>dit</i> Labbé and Duchesne from Pont-l'Abbé-d'Arnoult in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie-Madeleine Ménard in Montreal, QC, in 1697. — In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Alexis Dulignon <i>dit</i> Chevalier (a descendant of Jean Dulignon from La Rochefoucaud in Charente, France), who married Judith (de) Billy in Louiseville, QC, in 1778. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavalier","meanings":["French (southern): variant of   Chevalier   ‘knight, rider’. This surname is also found in Britain, where it is of Huguenot origin.","History: André Cavalier from Bordeaux in Gironde, France, married first Isabelle-Barbe Brousillon in New Orleans, LA, <i>c.</i> 1760, and second Marie-Jeanne Le Cossec/Cosse in New Orleans in 1770."]},{"name":"Chevallier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Blanchard, Christophe, Francois.","French: variant of   Chevalier   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]},{"name":"Olimpia","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: Heavenly"],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":31,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":40,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Olimpia Chevaler was born about 1184, in Bristol, Gloucestershire, England as the daughter of William Franc Chevaler. She married Ralph de Wilington Constable of Bristol Castle about 1193, in Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 1 August 1242, at the age of 59."},"et":{"Abt 1184–1 August 1242":"umbes 1184–1. august 1242","1179–Male":"1179–Surnud","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1180–1242":"1180–1242","1210–1256":"1210–1256","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","about 1193":"umbes 1193","1242":"1242","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","1180":"1180","Abt 1184":"umbes 1184","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1179":"1179","Abt 1210":"umbes 1210","Bef 1242":"enne 1242","1210":"1210","1 August 1242":"1. august 1242","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1184–1 August 1242":"noin 1184–1. elokuuta 1242","1179–Male":"1179–Kuollut","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1180–1242":"1180–1242","1210–1256":"1210–1256","1141–Male":"1141–Kuollut","about 1193":"noin 1193","1242":"1242","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","1180":"1180","Abt 1184":"noin 1184","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1179":"1179","Abt 1210":"noin 1210","Bef 1242":"ennen vuotta 1242","1210":"1210","1 August 1242":"1. elokuuta 1242","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1184–1 August 1242":"environ 1184–1 août 1242","1179–Male":"1179–Décédé","1184–1242":"1184–1242","1180–1242":"1180–1242","1210–1256":"1210–1256","1141–Male":"1141–Décédé","about 1193":"environ 1193","1242":"1242","1141":"1141","1184":"1184","1180":"1180","Abt 1184":"environ 1184","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1179":"1179","Abt 1210":"environ 1210","Bef 12